Subsidy Trap
Cambridge, USA — No policy is as directly at odds between good economics and good politics as food and energy subsidies.
Unaffordable subsidies are becoming the core issue facing the three most important new world leaders. They are Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President Joko Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
The subsidy cuts that Sisi faces are better than expected.
In contrast, Modi is facing a worse situation than expected, and could even undermine the long-awaited World Trade Organization agreement.
While Jokowi's situation remains unclear.
In July, Sisi achieved something few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East have managed: he significantly reduced long-standing energy subsidies, raising prices by 41-78%.
Interestingly, there were almost no protests of opposition.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs more than $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
Bread prices have remained at extremely low levels, often used to feed animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut such subsidies often sparked unrest, even toppling governments.
But the government of Xixi seems to be able to make progress in this area.
Bread subsidies have been reduced by 13%.
Xixi had no choice.
Even after the subsidy cuts, the current government's budget deficit target for the next fiscal year reached 10% of GDP (it would have been 14% without the subsidy cuts).
However, few expected that the relatively inexperienced Westy would be able to act more swiftly than Modi in the turbulent political environment. Modi, who won the prime ministership with a commanding democratic majority, was eager to implement comprehensive economic reforms.
In Indonesia, Jokowi inherited the long-standing fuel subsidy, which amounted to as high as $21 billion annually (equivalent to 20% of government spending), placing a heavy burden on the country.
The outgoing Susilo had already taken a brave first step a year earlier by raising fuel prices.
Jokowi's advisors suggested reducing the remaining subsidies, and he himself bluntly stated that the plan would be implemented gradually over four years.
Economists confidently oppose commodity subsidies, as agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In imperfectly competitive markets, the government — — rather than large private monopolies — — is the root cause.
Critics of the invisible hand point out that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main reasons for government intervention.
The controversy surrounding food and fossil fuel subsidies arises because they often claim to promote environmental or equality goals, but in reality, they are ineffective for these objectives and often have the opposite effect.
Only less than 20% of Egypt's food subsidies actually reach the poor.
Most gasoline subsidies in many countries benefit the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies go to the poorest population, while 52.6% flow into the pockets of the richest.
Overall, far less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies go to the poorest 20% of the population.
Subsidies for food and energy can also distort public policy, as evidenced by Modi's government that sought to protect agricultural subsidies in India.
In fact, Modi's government vetoed the World Trade Organization compromise, resulting in the loss of the most significant progress in multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Subsidies in agriculture can sometimes benefit producers at the expense of consumers, particularly in poor countries; and sometimes benefit consumers at the expense of producers, particularly in rich countries.
India's policy aims to achieve both.
As a result, India accomplished a feat: distributing wheat to consumers at artificially low prices, while at the same time experiencing oversupply, because farmers receive high prices.
(Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs — electricity, water, and fertilizers — which have caused environmental damage.
) The government purchased large quantities of corrupted rice and wheat, and the way in which a small portion was distributed to consumers was both corrupt and contrary to the goal of helping the poor.
The government may continue to maintain subsidies and purchase storage.
But it knows that this would violate World Trade Organization rules.
Since it cannot permanently change these rules, Modi simply vetoed the World Trade Organization's eagerly anticipated Trade Facilitation Agreement.
Once subsidies are implemented, it is difficult to reverse them.
When world commodity prices rise (as they did in the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot isolate them from shocks.
But people accustomed to government-set food and energy prices will demand that the government take responsibility.
This forms a strong argument for not implementing subsidies from the beginning.
However, this does not mean that once subsidies are implemented, maintaining them is necessarily the best choice for savvy politicians.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents might also erupt.
Similarly, if the growing gap eventually leads to even larger retail price hikes, slow-moving leaders will not benefit either.
In an ideal scenario, while reducing subsidies for food and energy, other more efficient measures to support low-income populations should be adopted.
Developing countries have already gained considerable experience in effective transfer mechanisms, such as Mexico's conditional cash transfer program (Progresa-Oportunidades) and Brazil's Bolsa Família program, as well as India's Unique Identification (UID) system, which represents technological innovation.
However, some countries are forced to make adjustments only when a budget crisis occurs, and they may not have the funds available for transfer payments to alleviate suffering.
Shrewd politicians might consider implementing unpopular adjustments right at the beginning of their tenure.
Jokowi and Widodo have adopted this approach.
Modi, who won a landslide victory in the election under the slogan of market reforms, has already fallen behind.
